I manage secrets in Terraform by storing them in external secret managers like AWS Secrets Manager or HashiCorp Vault instead of 
hardcoding them in code. I also mark sensitive values as sensitive = true and ensure Terraform state is encrypted and 
access-controlled.

I prefer using a secret manager such as AWS Secrets Manager or HashiCorp Vault, because they provide centralized storage, 
access control, auditing, and rotation of secrets.

| Feature            | What it does                  |
| ------------------ | ----------------------------- |
| `sensitive = true` | hides in CLI output           |
| `encrypt = true`   | encrypts state file at rest   |
| IAM policy         | controls who can access state |
| Secrets Manager    | stores secrets properly       |


two ways

1st way
----------------------------------------
Manual secret approach (your code)
You create secret → Terraform reads it → Terraform uses it
-------------------------------------------
via console: Secrets Manager → Store a new secret → "Other type of secret" → key/value pairs for username and password.

| Key        | Value           |
| ---------- | --------------- |
| `username` | `admin`         |
| `password` | `MyPassword123` |


it should look like:

Key         Value
-------------------------
username    admin
password    MyPassword123

Step 2

Give the secret a name, for example:

terraform/db-secret

Step 3

For this demo:

Leave Automatic rotation disabled.
Click Next.

Step 4

Review and click Store.

Create main.tf:

Step 1: Read secret from AWS Secrets Manager

provider "aws" {
  region = "us-east-2"
}

data "aws_secretsmanager_secret" "db" {
  name = "terraform/db-secret"
}

data "aws_secretsmanager_secret_version" "db" {
  secret_id = data.aws_secretsmanager_secret.db.id
}

locals {
  db_secret = jsondecode(data.aws_secretsmanager_secret_version.db.secret_string)
}

Step 2: Create RDS instance

resource "aws_db_instance" "mysql" {
  identifier = "my-rds-db"

  engine         = "mysql"
  engine_version = "8.0"

  instance_class = "db.t3.micro"

  allocated_storage = 20

  db_name  = "appdb"

  username = local.db_secret.username
  password = local.db_secret.password

  skip_final_snapshot = true

  publicly_accessible = false
}

🚀 What happens here
Your secret in AWS:

{
  "username": "admin",
  "password": "MyPassword123"
}

Terraform flow:

Secrets Manager
      ↓
Terraform reads secret
      ↓
Creates RDS instance
      ↓
Uses username + password securely

⚠️ Important interview point

Even though we are not hardcoding:

❗ The password may still be stored in Terraform state file

So always:

Use encrypted backend (S3 + KMS)
Restrict access to state file
Never expose state publicly

🎯 Interview-ready answer

If asked:

“How do you use secrets in RDS with Terraform?”

“I store the DB credentials in AWS Secrets Manager and fetch them using Terraform data sources. Then I pass them to the RDS resource. 
This avoids hardcoding sensitive data, and I also ensure the Terraform state is encrypted because it may still contain sensitive values.”

2nd way
-------------------------------------------------------------
AWS managed password approach
AWS creates secret → RDS uses it → Terraform does NOT touch it
-----------------------------------------------------------------------
✅ Full Terraform Example (RDS + managed password)

provider "aws" {
  region = "us-east-2"
}

resource "aws_db_instance" "mysql" {
  identifier = "my-managed-rds"

  engine         = "mysql"
  engine_version = "8.0"

  instance_class = "db.t3.micro"

  allocated_storage = 20

  db_name = "appdb"

  username = "admin"

  # 🔐 AWS manages password automatically
  manage_master_user_password = true

  skip_final_snapshot = true

  publicly_accessible = false

  storage_encrypted = true
}

🔥 What happens internally

When you use:

AWS automatically:

1. Generates a strong password
2. Stores it in AWS Secrets Manager
3. Attaches it to RDS master user
4. Keeps it available for rotation

🔐 How do you retrieve it?
Option 1 (AWS Console)
Go to Secrets Manager
Open the generated secret
Click “Retrieve secret value”

🧠 Interview-ready answer

“When we set manage_master_user_password = true, AWS automatically generates and stores the master password in AWS Secrets Manager. 
Terraform does not handle or store the password, making it more secure and enabling features like automatic rotation and centralized 
secret management.”

🧾 Interview-ready answer

“When we use manage_master_user_password = true, AWS automatically generates the master password and stores it in Secrets Manager. 
No Lambda or manual process is involved. If we later enable rotation, AWS uses a Lambda function to periodically rotate the password 
and update both the database and the secret.”

🔐 It reduces secret exposure, but does NOT guarantee zero secrets in state
-----------------------------------------------------------------------
# main.tf
provider "aws" {
  region = "us-east-2"          // AWS region where all resources will be created
}

variable "db_password" {      -- it can be any name
  sensitive = true              // marks this variable as sensitive
                                // value will NOT be shown in terraform plan/apply output
                                // protects password from being exposed in logs
}

resource "aws_db_instance" "db" {
  identifier        = "mydb"        // name of the RDS instance visible in AWS console
  engine            = "mysql"       // database engine type - mysql, postgres, oracle etc
  instance_class    = "db.t3.micro" // RDS instance size - determines CPU and RAM
  allocated_storage = 20            // storage size in GB allocated for database
  username          = "admin"       // master username to login to database
  password          = var.db_password  // master password - comes from sensitive variable
                                       // never hardcode password directly here
  skip_final_snapshot = true        // skip taking a snapshot when DB is destroyed
                                    // set false in prod to keep backup before delete
}

---------------
#sensitive = true  →  hides the value in logs:
#encrypt = true    →  encrypts state file on disk in S3 in backend.tf // It encrypts the entire state file — not just passwords. // S3 SSE-S3 encryption (AES-256)    ← what encrypt = true does

“sensitive = true only hides secrets in CLI output, and S3 encryption only protects the state at rest. But Terraform state can still 
contain secrets and be accessed if IAM is misconfigured. AWS Secrets Manager provides centralized storage, access control, auditing, 
and rotation, which Terraform alone does not handle.”

🔥 One-line memory trick
sensitive = true → hides in output
encrypt = true = S3 encryption → protects disk
Secrets Manager → protects lifecycle + access + rotation

💥 Why AWS Secrets Manager exists

Because it solves problems Terraform does NOT solve:

1. Centralized secret storage

Instead of embedding secrets in infrastructure state.

2. Access control (IAM-based)

You can say:

EC2 role → can read secret
Terraform → can read secret
Developer → cannot

3. Rotation (BIG reason)

Secrets Manager supports:

automatic password rotation
database credential rotation without downtime

☁️ AWS password rotation (real-world)

Using AWS Secrets Manager, you can enable:

automatic rotation every X days (e.g., 30, 60, 90)
Lambda function handles updating DB password
apps keep working without downtime

✅ Automatic rotation (AWS way)

AWS uses a Lambda rotation function behind the scenes.

Flow:

Secrets Manager
      ↓
Generates new password
      ↓
Rotation Lambda runs
      ↓
Updates database password
      ↓
Updates secret in Secrets Manager

Terraform does NOT do this.

4. Audit tracking

You get:

who accessed secret
when
from where

Terraform state does not give this level of audit control.

5. Separation of concerns

| System          | Purpose                     |
| --------------- | --------------------------- |
| Terraform       | Infrastructure provisioning |
| Secrets Manager | Secret lifecycle management |




